NOAO2019B-9990.title: Probing Fast and Dark Side of Transients
NOAO2019B-9990.abstract: Extreme transients defying the normal paradigm of supernova explosions have been found, but the majority of them have non-prompt discoveries and lack of a detailed follow-up, severely diminishing the scientific return. LSST will make it more challenging boosting the number of yearly discoveries by a factor of 100, making it almost impossible to find such extreme transients using current methodology. The immediate objective is to improve our understanding of three types of transients which, until now, lack very early observations. These classes are 1- rapidly evolving, 2 - in low-luminosity hosts and 3 - in remote locations. Our long-term goal is to provide a well-studied sample of such transients to train machine learning classifier in preparation for the LSST era.

NOAO2019B-0992.title: Spectroscopic classification of microlensing source stars
NOAO2019B-0992.abstract: The phenomena of microlensing can be used to measure the physical properties (mass(es), projected orbital separation for binaries) for lensing objects which are otherwise to faint and/or distant to be observed, and thus can determine the mass functions and galactic distribution of a wide range of objects, from planets to black holes.  However, microlensing models have many degeneracies, of which the most important is the mass-distance dependance of the characteristic Einstein radius.  In order to determine the physical properties of the lens, a second constraint is almost always required.  Most commonly, this is provided by a measurement of the lensing parallax combined with an estimate of the apparent angular size of and distance to the source star.  The former is routinely measured through one of a) second-order effects in long-timescale events, b) simultaneous satellite observations or c) simultaneous terrestrial observations, but the source star properties are usually derived from stellar models based on the multi-band photometry of the source.  This technique becomes uncertain for some spectral types, and leads to ambiguity between dwarfs and giants.  Spectroscopy offers more reliable classifications but the magnitude range of microlensing events at peak (I~16-19mag) means that it requires a large aperture facility, and the SOAR/Goodman instrument is ideal for this purpose.

NOAO2019B-0991.title: Time-Domain spectroscopy of young stars in Orion OB1
NOAO2019B-0991.abstract:
Low-mass pre-main sequence stars (K and M type), also known as T Tauri stars,
exhibit enhanced activity, both stellar and circumstellar.  Active chromospheres power emission
lines like Halpha, and stars surrounded by accretion disks produce a strong and wide Halpha profile,
idue to material infalling at free-fall velocities onto the stellar surface. The resulting hot shocks produce
continuum emission that can veil absorption features, specially in the optical, and contribute significant
excess at UV wavelengths. As both stellar activity and accretion can be highly variable, these features
change with time. However, there are few time-domain spectroscopic studies of T Tauri stars, and
essentially none for stars nearing the end of their accretion phase, a stage when young  planets are
expected to be in the last stages of formation.
We will use Goodman on SOAR to obtain time-series spectroscopy of a sample of T Tauri stars in
the Orion OB1 region, with ages 4-10 Myr, showing signatures of very low accretion levels.
This study will provide new insight into how sun-like stars end their accretion phase, which has
important implications for our understanding of the conditions for planet formation.
